==Old English==

===Etymology===
Common Germanic ''*petwōr'', from Proto-Indo-European ''*kwetwōr''.  Cognates include Old High German [[fior]] (German ''[[vier]]''), Old Saxon [[fiuwar]] (Dutch ''[[vier]]''), Old Norse ''[[fjórir]]'', Gothic [[𐍆𐌹𐌳𐍅𐍉𐍂]].  The IE root was also the source of Common Slavic *''[[četiri]]'' (Russian [[четыре]]), Old Irish [[cethair]], Greek ''[[τέσσαρες]]'', Latin ''[[quattuor]]''.

